      "id": "review::.::holistic::api_surface_coherence::jwt_token_generation_contract_is_hidden_by_overloads",
      "confidence": "high",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "summary": "`JwtTokenService.generateToken` overloads hide which token schema a caller receives",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "api_surface_coherence",
        "related_files": [
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/service/JwtTokenService.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/controller/AuthController.java",
          "backend/src/main/java/com/demo/sso/service/OAuth2SuccessHandler.java",
          "backend/src/test/java/com/demo/sso/controller/ControllerIntegrationTest.java"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`JwtTokenService.generateToken(String email, String googleId)` always builds the legacy subject/`googleId` token, while `generateToken(User user)` conditionally emits V2 claims or delegates back to the legacy overload depending on rollout settings.",
          "The shared method name `generateToken` does not tell callers whether the result will contain legacy `googleId` claims or V2 `ver`/`provider`/`providerUserId`/`email` claims, and production callers use a different overload than several integration tests."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Split legacy and current minting into explicitly named entrypoints (for example `generateLegacyToken(...)` and `generateUserToken(...)`) and keep only one default public path for production callers so the token contract is obvious from the call site.",
        "reasoning": "",
        "summary_hash": "f0fd48cb"
      },
      "status": "open",
      "kind": "issue",
